<section>
<h2><i class="fas fa-project-diagram"></i> Project Overview</h2>
<p>
<strong>MedEase</strong> is an intelligent hospital management system created as part of the
<em>CMP216: Web Applications and Cloud Services</em> module at Newcastle College University Centre.
       This system was developed by <strong>Arshad Aslam</strong> in 2025 to showcase practical skills in full-stack
       development, UI/UX design, cloud integration, and accessibility.
</p>
</section>
<section>
<h2><i class="fas fa-bullseye"></i> Purpose</h2>
<p>
       MedEase aims to support hospitals and clinics with an intuitive and reliable platform for managing
       patients and room allocations. Designed for healthcare staff with minimal technical knowledge, the
       application prioritises usability, responsiveness, and visual clarity.
</p>
</section>
<section>
<h2><i class="fas fa-star"></i> Key Features</h2>
<ul>
<li>📝 Add, edit, view, and delete patient records</li>
<li>🛏️ Full hospital room management with occupancy controls</li>
<li>🌐 MongoDB Atlas for secure, cloud-based data handling</li>
<li>🌗 Dark mode toggle with persistent localStorage setting</li>
<li>🚨 Error logging using Winston and custom 404/500 pages</li>
<li>📱 Fully responsive design across all screen sizes</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section>
<h2><i class="fas fa-cogs"></i> Technologies Used</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Node.js & Express.js</strong> – Backend server and routing framework</li>
<li><strong>MongoDB Atlas</strong> – Cloud-based NoSQL database</li>
<li><strong>EJS</strong> – Dynamic HTML rendering with embedded JavaScript</li>
<li><strong>CSS3</strong> – Custom responsive styling and dark mode support</li>
<li><strong>Font Awesome</strong> – Iconography for improved user interface</li>
<li><strong>Docker</strong> – Optional containerisation for development and deployment</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section>
<h2><i class="fab fa-docker"></i> Docker Integration</h2>
<p>
       MedEase includes optional <strong>Docker</strong> support, allowing the entire app and database to be
       containerised and run seamlessly across different environments.
</p>
<p>To run using Docker Compose:</p>
<pre><code>docker-compose up --build</code></pre>
<p>
       This makes the application portable and ideal for cloud deployment or demonstration.
</p>
</section>
